            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Dmitri Volkova was born in Minsk, Belarus, in the waning years of the Soviet Union. His world was one of concrete apartment blocks and whispered conversations. His father, a factory engineer, taught him the logic of machinery, how to diagnose a fault by sound and touch. From a young age, Dmitri understood that everything, from a sputtering engine to a political system, was a mechanism that could break down.\n\nHe met his wife, Elena, at a pro-democracy rally in his late teens. She was fierce, an artist with an unshakeable belief in a better future. When the political climate grew oppressive, it was Elena who secured the papers to emigrate. They arrived in San Francisco in their early twenties with little more than their shared dreams. To honor their partnership and break from the past, Dmitri made the unorthodox choice to take her surname, Volkova.\n\nTheir new life was a struggle. His Belarusian technical school diploma meant little, so he took handyman jobs, learning English on construction sites and in boiler rooms. His break came when he landed a junior maintenance position at a burgeoning biotech lab in Mission Bay. While PhDs worked on gene therapies, Dmitri was the one ensuring the sensitive climate-control systems never failed. His meticulous nature and innate ability to fix complex equipment earned him respect and, over fifteen years, a steady climb to Facilities and Operations Manager.\n\nTragedy struck seven years ago when Elena died from a sudden illness. The loss hollowed him out, leaving his work as his only anchor. Now, Dmitri\u2019s life is a study in quiet routine. He lives in the same rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond they first shared, the fog rolling in off the Pacific a constant, comforting companion. His 6.5-mile commute on the N Judah is a silent ritual, a time to mentally prepare for the day. He is the invisible force that allows science to happen, the man who keeps the multi-million-dollar labs running flawlessly.\n\nDmitri\u2019s aspirations are modest. He finds a deep, quiet satisfaction in his competence and in creating an environment where others can achieve greatness. He dreams of one day saving enough to establish a small arts grant in Elena\u2019s name, a small mechanism to ensure her vibrant spirit continues to fuel creation in the city they chose as their own."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe first saw her at a rally in Minsk, a slash of defiant color in a sea of grey coats. While others chanted, Elena was painting a banner, her expression one of fierce concentration. He, who understood the world as a series of fragile mechanisms, saw her not as a protestor, but as a creator. She was building something, not just railing against what was broken. This single moment rewired his soul, introducing him to the powerful machinery of hope and marking the true beginning of his life. It happened in his late teens.\n\n2.\nTheir first morning in San Francisco, they stood at the window of their empty Inner Richmond apartment as a wall of fog rolled in from the ocean. It should have been desolate, but Elena smiled and called it a \u201cclean canvas.\u201d It was a moment of pure, terrifying potential. With the city obscured, all they had was each other and the room they stood in. This memory cemented the fog not as gloomy, but as a promise\u2014a blank slate on which they would build their new life together. This was in their early twenties.\n\n3.\nAn alarm shrieked through the biotech lab; a multi-million-dollar freezer was failing. While PhDs panicked, Dmitri knelt and listened, tuning out the noise to hear the machine\u2019s true language. It was a faint, irregular hum his father had taught him to recognize. He pinpointed a faulty capacitor\u2014a five-dollar part. As silence returned, he felt a profound respect from the scientists. It was the first time his old-world, hands-on knowledge was truly valued in this new life, solidifying his purpose. This was roughly twelve years ago.\n\n4.\nComing home to the apartment the first night after her death was the hardest thing he\u2019d ever done. The silence was an active, aggressive presence where her laughter used to be. Her half-finished painting sat on its easel by the window, the vibrant colors a cruel mockery of the world\u2019s new emptiness. He realized then that she had been the central, load-bearing pillar of his life, and now that she was gone, he feared an imminent and total collapse. This was seven years ago.\n\n5.\nOn his daily N Judah commute, passing through the Duboce Triangle, he saw a new, chaotic mural splashed across a building. His first, instant thought was, *Elena would have loved its energy.* The familiar pang of grief was there, but it was followed by a quiet, determined calm. He unconsciously touched his wallet, feeling the folded paper where he tracked his savings. The art grant wasn't just a fantasy; it was a blueprint. He was building a new mechanism, one to keep her spirit working in the world. This was last week."
